post-details.content:
Trigger a page transition dynamically with `useRouter`.
```js
const router = useRouter()

const onClick = () => {
  router.push({ path: '/new/path' })
}
```

This is an alternative to using `<NuxtLink>`.

If you have custom fetching logic, you can wrap the logic inside `useAsyncData`.

Just like `useFetch`, `useAsyncData` will make sure the same data don't have to be refetched again on the client side.
```js
const { data } = await useAsyncData('post-list', () => {
  return getPostList()
})
```

Unlike `useFetch`, you need to provide a cache key (`post-list` in the above example).

Validation logic can be registered for a route via `definePageMeta`.
```js
definePageMeta({
  validate: async (route) => {
    // return true or false
  }
})
```

You can set `<title>`, `<meta>`, and `<link>` with the `useHead` composable.
```js
useHead({
  title: 'Home',
  meta: [
    { name: 'description', content: 'A Nuxt Site' }
  ],
  link: [
    { rel: 'stylesheet', href: 'style/url' }
  ]
})
```

A Nuxt app can be configured to render entirely on the client side, just like a regular Vue.js app.

You just need to set it with the `routeRules` option:
```js
//nuxt.config.ts
export default defineNuxtConfig({
  routeRules: {
    '/**': { ssr: false }
  }
})
```

A Nuxt app can be generated entirely at build time.

You just need to set it with the `routeRules` option:
```js
export default defineNuxtConfig({
  routeRules: {
    '/**': { prerender: true }
  }
})
```

The app will be able to get served without an app server.

A Nuxt app can be statically regenerated from time to time.

You can specifiy when you want a page to be regenerated:
```js
export default defineNuxtConfig({
  routeRules: {
    '/**': { swr: 60 }
  }
})
```

In this example, the pages will be regenerated no more than once every 60 seconds.

Create an API route with `defineEventHandler`.
```js
// server/api/sample-route.js
export default defineEventHandler(event => {
  return {
    data: 1
  }
})
```

This route can now be accessed with the path **/api/sample-route**.

Different from route middleware, server middleware only executes on the server.
```js
// server/middleware/sample-middleware.js
export default defineEventHandler(event => {
  // your middleware code
})
```

This middleware will be automatically registered and run.

A middleware is a special function that gets executed before a route.

You can create a middleware in the **middleware** folder:
```js
// middleware/sample-middleware.js
export default defineNuxtRouteMiddleware((to, from) => {
  // your middleware code
})
```

You can return either `abortNavigation()` or `navigateTo(path)` inside the middleware.

Then in the component, you have to register the middleware:

```js
definePageMeta({
  middleware: [
    'sample-middleware'
  ]
})
```

A middleware can be also be created without an external file.

You can insert it as a function in the `middleware` array of the page:
```js
definePageMeta({
  middleware: [
    function (to, from) {
      // your middleware code
    }
  ]
})
```

Middlewares will be executed in the same order that they appear in the array.
